Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
Ukraine's parliament today rejected a proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the release of the former prime minister, but MPs rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing an agreement with Russia disadvantageous to Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The sentence is not yet final, the appeal court has the obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political vendetta by the regime, and even in the West doubts have been raised about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Penal Code convicting the former prime minister was supported by 147 MPs in the vote.
For its adoption, 226 votes were required.
