Brand story:
The innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If someone were looking for a term that defined IBM's strategy with great precision, the closest would be "long-term."
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and, nevertheless, a hundred years have passed since its founding.
The basis of this long-term character was laid by the first head of the firm, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the motto that many of the world's problems can be solved if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his hallmark, around which the life of the future giant will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
