The value of IBM shares since the beginning of 2008 has grown stratospherically to 120%, the net profit of the company has not stopped increasing.
IBM's currency is to change everything except its value.
One can therefore expect that when the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will hold on.
IBM History: From the Cheese Slicer to Spaceflight
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The IBM name was adopted as early as 1924 - originally it was a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation that gave rise to IBM's birth stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He owned inventions such as the famous "clock", which allows you to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint hired the head of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The new leader eclipsed IBM's founder (Watson's ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are built).
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began producing and selling everything from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During Watson's first four years at the helm, turnover doubled by $9 million and the company's vast expansion across continents began.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, almost forty years in the boss's chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 60s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights into space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the computer standard of that time, came to market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, in turn, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer a complete advice and services of high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid for these last three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, "a smarter planet".
Its aim is to make more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned or circumstances have improved, for example in terms of transport and city management.
For the commerce sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smart Commerce" platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 it opened a branch in Czechoslovakia at the time, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Here today, IBM ČR also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Also here is a world-famous research team working with speech recognition.
