How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of that time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist bloc, since travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea) Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when travel to Yugoslavia could be traveled, however, afterwards the Yugoslav regime leaned westwards and the travel of Czech tourists was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even in socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at that time, but one had to queue up with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West was not granted to "politically unreliable people," who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, with no guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way of travelling of the Czechs has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 it was the only time spent holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria for us, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware, that the current favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of the Yugoslavia of that time.
At the beginning of the 90s, visa-free travel to neighbouring Western European states was imposed, which led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not look fed up with excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris groups of Czechs slept in parks in tents, since our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was to take with them the food (preserves, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech koruna, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was rising, and so were average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in demand for travel.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began regularly preparing for travel using charter connections from 1997 onwards, which dramatically lowered travel prices compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of discounts for passenger volume.
At the end of the 90s of the last century, Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the USA, which further simplified our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, thanks to a huge demand, and it was to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists depart every year to distant and hot countries. This winter it will already fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, symbolizing our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, more than CZK 15,000 per head were spent on trips abroad, including expenses on the place of stay.
Ordinary General Assembly called to elect the president, which could end up deadlocked again.
For almost five months Czech football has been without a president and it is likely that Ivan Hašek's successor as President of the Czech Football Association (FAČR) will not be known even after the next Extraordinary General Assembly that will take place this Thursday in Nymburk.
In fact, no agreement has yet been reached on the voting rules to be followed.
Without them, it will not be possible to vote even to choose between the three candidates.
Those interested in presiding over Czech football are Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
Hašek resigned from his post in June, but not before summoning his colleagues in order to find a strong person who would know how to deal with football in the future.
However, after the conclusion of the Hašek era, a controversy broke out between the two federations of the association unable to reach an agreement to choose a common candidate.
This was evident on 16 September when the new president had to be elected.
The delegates of the General Assembly met in vain at the National House (Národní dům), located in the Prague neighborhood of Smíchov, because the talks had been blocked and not only in terms of the method of election.
No consensus was reached as to who in the General Assembly had the right to vote - only legal representatives or also delegates with full powers.
From that moment and because of this single point, there was a partial agreement, also supported by the recommendation of the Institute of State and Law, according to which representation by full powers is not possible.
However, disputes over the electoral code remain open.
More light on the situation could no longer be shed even by the Executive Committee which, in its meetings, ordinary or extraordinary, basically did not resolve anything.
The opinion on the possibility of voting has changed a couple of times already, but the nerve center remains the same.
The question is: how to proceed in the third round to avoid deadlock?
"The dispute revolves around whether to proceed according to the statutes or find another model," says Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-presidents of the FAČR, which, from the direction of the association, represents professional football.
According to the model proposed in the statutes, in the third round the candidate with the highest percentage of support in the federation to which he will present his candidacy will win.
The Moravian Region is willing to reach a compromise so that the candidate with the highest total percentage of votes in both federations can win.
The Bohemian part, however, imposes the condition that the winner, according to these percentage calculations, must have a majority of at least two-thirds.
"This would, however, detract from the meaning of the previous two rounds and completely negate the concept of the bicameral system," is how Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian side, according to which it would be best not to touch the order and vote according to the applicable statutes.
Surprisingly, Tomaš Paclík also agrees with this, although it is assumed that the electoral regulations established by the statutes of all candidates are more suitable for Pelta.
"I would like it to be voted to the maximum according to the statutes."
"Lest any nonsense be invented about representatives like at the last General Assembly," says the owner of Victoria Plzen, who is running for the first time as a candidate and who directs his remarks mainly against Pelta.
Pelta remains optimistic.
According to him, in Nymburk the new president will be decided and he believes that the candidates in the future will cooperate constructively.
"All passions will be tempered by today's match of our national team at the European Championship.
"Football will once again be the protagonist, and thus cooperation will be more comfortable," says the representative of Jablonice, who of the three candidates has more experience in football management, both professionally and regionally.
Rajchl is the most reticent.
"I hope an agreement will be reached, but, unfortunately, the situation is much more complicated."
"It's not about the conflict between bohemians and Moravians, but there are attempts to adjust the rules to their own convenience."
"This may result in a new blockade of the General Assembly."
"Anyway, I hope common sense will prevail," Rajchl said.
There is not much time left for all parties to reach an agreement.
Some negotiations had to take place in Montenegro, but who can know until the match starts if the football team will be complete?
The special plane, in which they had to travel to Podgorica, among others the vice presidents Dalibor Kucera and Rajchl, has not left this morning due to technical problems in Prague, having to look for an alternative to transport part of the executive committee to the place where the qualifying match will take place.
Perhaps the decisive meeting, finally, could be the one that will take place at the ministerial level, which, according to what they say, will be held this Wednesday.
Josef Dobeš, Minister of Education, Youth and Sports, would very much like to incorporate the divided parties into the country's most powerful sports organization so that an agreement can be reached.
The stakes are high: state subsidies, the credibility of football and also the upcoming General Assembly of the Central Committee of the Czechoslovak Sports Federation (ČSTV) which will try to give a new direction to Czech sport after the financial problems of the Sazka lottery house.
Paclík will fight for the presidency, because he does not find a more suitable candidate.
If the head of the Pilsen footballers, Tomaš Paclik, before the extraordinary General Assembly knew the name of a suitable candidate who satisfied all his ideas about the new president of the Czech Football Association (FAČR), he would not present himself as a candidate for such an important position.
