The 21st house in Vienna
The pavilion moved
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups and downs and a happy ending, the pavilion of the Austrian Universal Exhibition in Brussels in 1958 won awards, was in Vienna for a museum, stood empty and crumbled.
It is now reopened as an exhibition house.
Modern postgerra architecture is passionate, clear forms, glass halls, brave curves and new building materials, typical of thinking about technical progress, for which the Austrian pavilion of architect Karl Schwanzer for the Universal Exhibition in Brussels in 1958 is a suitable and well-known example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion then won the Grand Prix of Architecture for its light, floating steel and glass construction.
The construction is considered to this day a contemporary landmark of architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built the Austrian pavilion at the next Universal Exhibition.
With its legendary four-cylinder tower for MBW plus the adjacent flattened building in Munich, it became internationally known.
Its pavilion, designed as a temporary exhibition building was erected after the universal exhibition at the Schweizer Garten next to Vienna's South Station, was refurbished in 1962 and inside a 20th century museum was inaugurated, it was called the "20th house".
The building was adequate but lacked the right spaces and technology for a museum; No wall to hang art, no good atmosphere.
Despite this it was used until contemporary art in Vienna had a new home.
The building has been empty since 2001 and is decaying more and more.
Currently, the architect Adolf Krischanitz renovated the pavilion, now calls it "house 21" and will be used in the future as a museum of contemporary art.
On Tuesday afternoon the belvedere museum, to which the house belongs, was inaugurated with the first exhibition, a stroke of luck in a way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, the new director of the Austrian belvedere gallery since 2007, achieved a new beginning.
Husslein-Arco, a doctor in art history with a considerable career, among other things, figure skater in her youth, later at Sotheby, the Guggenheim museum and founding director of the museum of modern art in Salzburg, carried out the reforms at the insistence of politicians and protectors of monuments, provided public funds and private sponsors and established their use.
With the exception of contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba of the homonymous foundation are exhibited, there should be a cafeteria and a bookshop and also an office building built.
Tight control, low budget
Krischanitz was the best choice to do so.
Not only because he sensitively reformed the secession of Joseph Olbrichs in Vienna, he expanded it and was awarded the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzwer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him an "important and immense place", in which he contemplated "almost every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the project and the problem of the building, which disappeared with his move to Vienna in his change of use with generosity and ease.
In the current renovations there are big problems, the building was "an energy eater," Krischanitz said.
The profile of the windows of the glass façade was changed, insulating glass reinforced with fiberglass was installed, and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Thermal bridges and steel beams were reinforced or replaced and asbestos roofs were rehabilitated.
Two basements were employed for the new use, a lowered light panel between the house and the street provides lighting, a bridge serves to enter the building almost new, but still the Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain, the house is painted in antique mahogany tones and protected against oxidation.
And the movie theater is exactly as it was before.
And all this with strict control by the monuments office and a low budget.
"I often had to find material that was good, cheap and also liked by the monument protection office," says Krischanitz, warning of rough soil in the basement.
Despite all the pressures, problems and renovations, the building remains flexible and light.
The pavilion "that came from Brussels" has been difficult, Krischanitz said recently, a typical "chance appearance in the history of the city."
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and that is why he wanted to "awaken the right consciousness".
In this case house 21 is not in the wrong place, an urban stroke of luck has happened. The all-new and planned "Central Station district", with housing and offices, is located next to the Schweizer Garten.
And perhaps another stroke of luck will happen: House 21 could receive a reinforcement from another construction by Krischanitz, since the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the temporary Berlin art room and, as you hear, negotiates with the city about a neighboring place in the Schweizer Garten.
