Peter Englund's intense and generous new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate Story of World War I, "begins with a long dramatis personae of the kind that can make your soul fall at your feet.
Here are some acting tips: Gently rip this page off and make it your bookmark.
He will get to know these people very well in Mr. Englund's novelistic narrative, and this dramatis personae will function as his GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, as one of his men and women, he is confused and helpless in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
What he has written here is an unusual book, which he aptly describes as "a work of anti-history."
It contains some notable names, important treatises or famous battles; There are virtually no ambassadors, fancy journalists, or discussions about tactics or material.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as "a book about how it happened." It is about "feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods."
"The Beauty and Pain of Battle" combines the wartime experiences of about 20 ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and clerks.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Some will become prisoners of war, or lose their limbs, go mad, or die.
Their lives flicker here like votive candles lit in a church; Some new ones are added to the mixture while others are turned off.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard history books.
It is also a corrective to the notion that World War I was only the disastrous trench warfare on the Western Front.
"The beauty and pain of battle" expertly moves through other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book have hives fall on them; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; Tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This is a moving book, almost from the beginning.
War floods the lives of these people like a natural catastrophe, a Hurricane Katrina that reeks of cordite.
When artillery fire is heard in the distance, and you are a woman who is at home with your children, do you stay or flee?
Anyway, who's coming?
Almost no one understands what is happening, or even why this war has to be fought.
"Lack of facts," Mr. Englund observes, "has been filled with conjectures, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
"The Beauty and Pain of Battle" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German sailor in the High Seas Fleet.
Their stories have been obtained mostly from memoirs, letters, and other previously published material.
