Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Are Studying You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy airing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to carrying out a massacre in Norway in July that left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time preceding his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After this summer's tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just log in to Facebook.
"We realized it wasn't that hard to reach them," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British think tank DEMOS.
Facebook's stash of personal information is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographics with scientific accuracy — the way marketers have been using for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then targeted ads to them, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes toward violence and optimism about their own future.
Arriving via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries — all without leaving the office.
"It's a totally new way of doing research," Bartlett says.
Some of the results aren't entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male, and angry about immigration.
However, in a kind of twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen."
DEMOS' work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming an important new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health issues to social trends as expressed in likes, wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom, driving the number of scholarly papers with the site's name in the title up to nearly 800% in the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to survey people in the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to go through the game, and they'd never allow you access," Bartlett says.
"Facebook removes all of that – you go to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address social-health issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and colleagues found that college students who talked about their drunken exploits on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student post too many status updates with their binges.
"You can't treat a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at Seattle's Children's Research Institute, the Washington Post said.
"We have found a way to identify at-risk children who would otherwise go undiagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "poking" its own population for data.
The site's Data Team has produced statistics on the state of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of voter turnout midway through the 2010 legislative term, and a National Happiness index (mainly using the information that can be accessed – digital freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make its vast amount of data available to others for the research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is an open bar for everyone.
"I don't think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the Knowledge Lab in London, of a 2006 study he conducted with students' public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know that some of the information in a user's profile and wall messages are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things," Selwyn says.
That's why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a paper clip and pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
"There's no substitute for going into the real world and talking to real people," he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about the social – and a lot of social research still happens offline."
"Cold and inhumane: Anders Behring Breivik makes his first public appearance in court
Anders Behring Breivik, the man who confessed to masterminding the two attacks that killed 77 people in Norway this summer, has described himself as a "resistance" fighter during his first public appearance at the Oslo court.
"I am a military commander in the Norwegian resistance movement and in the Knights Templar of Norway," he told a packed room of 500 people.
"I oppose the court because it received the mandate from organizations that support the ideology of hate and because it supports multiculturalism."
"I acknowledge the facts but I do not plead guilty."
Judge Torkjel Nesheim interrupted Breivik during that monologue, because he "didn't want to give Breivik the opportunity to use this hearing as a platform for him to express his views."
For the same reason he refused to allow Breivik, who brought a written speech in advance, to address the relatives of his victims at the end of the hearing.
Nesheim also ordered police to keep Breivik in custody for 12 more weeks, barred him from media access for four weeks, and said authorities would have to have strict control over all visits and correspondence for eight weeks.
About 30 survivors and relatives of the victims attended the hearing.
Some came hoping to look Breivik in the eye, others to confirm that he is being held under lock and key.
Everyone attended with the aim of moving towards the conclusion.
"I thought it looked cold and inhumane," one Utoya survivor told Norwegian broadcaster NRK.
"It was awkward, but for me it was a step forward after seeing and hearing the suspect."
Dressed in a dark suit and blue tie, Breivik remained calm and professional throughout the audience and looked reporters and survivors in the eye as he entered and exited the building.
Despite Breivik's bizarre notion of being part of a larger "resistance" movement, the judge determined he is not mentally ill, and said there is no evidence he acted with accomplices.
Some may be comforted that the July 22 attacks appear to be the work of an extremist rather than a group of radicals.
But that doesn't automatically soften the pain and confusion an entire nation still feels.
"I'd like it to look like a monster, but it doesn't look like it," said a relative of one victim.
"It would be much easier if it looked like it."
7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Lost Interview Shown in Theater This Week
Following Steve Jobs' death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford – distinguishing the tech genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a newly rediscovered Jobs interview that has been dusted off in a preview of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was certainly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a junkie of flowcharts – a man who believed many executives suffered "a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [But] there's an enormous amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and sat down for more than an hour with Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At the time, barely 10 years had passed since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensely at his new computer company NeXT, hoping for popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transportation.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This archival material, slightly reissued, is the basis of Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, 68 minutes, which arrives in Landmark theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
To someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to lay out his tech philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers — 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs' perfectionism surfaces, where he seems impatient because of Cringely's questions, pushing him to go faster toward the most important issues or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, the iPod or the iPhone, there's something strangely prescient about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It's one thing to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in the business, I always asked, 'Why do you do things?' and the answers you are invariably given are, 'Oh, that's just the way it's done.'
No one knows why he does what he does, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs takes into detail his efforts to simplify Apple's accounting.
Baffled by the way costs were recorded – often starting with a "standard cost" that was done with a good eye, and then adjusted with a "variable" – he developed an automated factory that ensured they could determine business costs in detail.
On the joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak – a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make free long-distance calls.
Extensively has been written about the device, but Jobs' euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a payphone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world a half-dozen times and you were screaming through the pay phone and coming back a minute later to the pay phone next door," Jobs says with a chuckle.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world."
The two of us, we didn't know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak to the pope, while doing his best Henry Kissinger impersonation.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the pope himself was awakened to answer the phone.
On falling in love with technology (and selling over the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs landed a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a noticeable influence on me, it was the only company I had ever seen at that age and it shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made."
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a little cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a ride to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
Early in his career, as he set about selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a customer if he could assemble the entire equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments... They were yelling at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and went outside and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On large companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple's renaissance, Jobs prophetically foresaw how many industry leaders would stumble on his vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers and printers, so what?"
You have a monopoly on market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is these kinds of people who end up running companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the forum for decision making.
The product genius that led to that monopoly position rots because of people who don't have the notion of good products vs. bad products – the knowledge of the necessary craft.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took defeat from victory.
On innovation as artistic expression:
"There's a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... As the big idea evolves, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make – some things you can't make electrons do, glass does, robots make them, factories do.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end it all comes down to taste – it comes down to trying to expose yourself to the best that a team of humans has ever done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you're doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed about stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren't for computer science, I might be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas dine with health care law rivals as court accepts case
On the day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to examine the politically contentious question of whether they would accept the challenge to President Obama's health care law, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were feted at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will present the case to the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to thoroughly study the requests for review.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging total health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying cry for conservative activists across the country.
The justices agreed to admit the lawsuit and, in fact, a historic 5 1/2 hour argument is expected in March, and the result will likely further muddy the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court's decision is known.
The lawyer who will appear in court and argue that the law should be scrapped will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. attorney general during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement's law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a longtime group dedicated to upholding conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that defied the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel, hours after the court's preliminary hearing on the case.
Among the attendees was, among others, Mitch McConnell, the top Republican in the Senate and an outspoken opponent of the health care law.
The special guests at dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
It's nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it's not something that conflicts with ethical standards.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct governing the actions of lower federal magistrates.
If they weren't, they could be said to fall under Canon Code 4C, which says, "A judge may attend fundraisers of law-related and other organizations, although the judge may not be a speaker, a guest of honor, or feature on the program of such an event."
However, Scalia and Thomas' absolute proximity to two of the law firms in the case, as well as a firm with enormous financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in government.
"This stunning ethical gap and disregard for the code runs counter to the demands of several justices that the court abides by the same rules that apply to all federal judges," said Bob Edgar, the president of Common Cause.
"The judges were feted at a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have cases pending before the court."
Their appearance and assistance at fundraising for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in critics who say they too easily mix the court's activity with the agenda pushed by groups like the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it is Justice Elena Kagan who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan served as attorney general for the Obama administration when the first legal challenges to the law were filed in trial court.
Her critics have pressed for Kagan to refrain from hearing the case, saying she was too involved in upholding the law to now be impartial.
Kagan has given no indication that he will do so.
Boeing receives record $18 billion order
Emirates is ordering 50 Boeing 777 twin-aisle aircraft, with an option for 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliners to Oman Air, a deal valued at more than a billion dollars.
It rarely makes the news when a company gets an order for 50 units of its product.
But it's a big deal when the company is planemaker Boeing Co. and the asking price for the 50 planes amounts to a record $18 billion.
It's as big as the place where Boeing received the order from: the Middle East, a growing gold mine of future aircraft orders.
In a study released Monday, the Chicago company estimates that over the next 20 years airlines in the Middle East will need 2,520 planes worth $450 billion.
Boeing announced over the weekend its largest-ever order for commercial airplanes worth in dollars — 50 Boeing 777 twin-aisle jets.
The successful order came from Emirates airline in Dubai.
The airline also has an option to buy 20 more planes, bringing the total selling price to $26 billion, Boeing announced at the 2011 Dubai Air Show.
Then, on Monday, Boeing said Oman Air had ordered six Boeing 787-8s, the so-called Dreamliner, which boasts spectacular fuel economy and passenger services.
The sale price for six of them is more than a billion dollars.
"This clearly has a huge positive effect for Boeing," said Morningstar analyst Neal Dihora.
"The quality of these particular customers is very strong."
Many Middle Eastern airlines are owned by their oil-producing nations.
So, not only do they have the money to pay for planes, but an increase in fuel prices – usually harmful to airlines, because it's one of the biggest costs – isn't that damaging, because the country is making money from rising oil prices.
That's important because they're less likely than other airlines to cancel or delay flight orders when fuel prices rise, Dihora said.
"They have a natural protection," he said.
The Emirates' order solidifies Boeing's leadership in the widebody market and helps keep rival Airbus SAS's attempt to encroach on its dominance with the A350 passenger jet at bay.
Boeing's victory at the air show comes four months after Airbus said it would delay the debut of the larger A350, which competes directly with the 777-300ER.
It delayed the debut to add more momentum after customers demanded an increase in payload and range.
Boeing Co shares rose 1.5 percent to $67.94.
Mexico's President's Sister Apparently Defeated in Michoacan Vote
Luisa Maria Calderon says drug traffickers helped her PRI opponent, Fausto Vallejo, in the race for governor.
President Felipe Calderon's sister appears to have lost her candidacy for governor of Michoacan during the violent state's election, and she claimed Monday that drug traffickers helped tilt the race in favor of one of her opponents.
Preliminary results gave Fausto Vallejo of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, the lead in the Western state race for governor.
"The intervention of organized crime throughout the electoral process and, especially yesterday, is alarming, not only for Michoacán, but for the whole country," Luisa María Calderón said in a radio interview a day after Sunday's vote.
"They threatened our candidates, our poll workers... They took over the ballot boxes, set up barricades... and ordered people to vote" for the PRI.
The PRI ruled Mexico for seven decades until it lost the presidency in 2000.
However, it is the staging of a comeback, and victory in Michoacan is an important step in that effort.
The PRI hopes to win the presidential election in July.
Vallejo appears to have narrowly edged out Calderon, who had led the polls before the election.
Calderon, a candidate from his brother's conservative National Action Party, or PAN, refused to recognize Vallejo as the winner.
Silvano Aureoles, the left-wing candidate for the Democratic Revolution Party, or PRD, who currently holds the governor's office, came in third, a major defeat for the divided and unfortunate left ahead of the 2012 presidential election.
Aureoles also declined to acknowledge the preliminary results.
Vallejo, a former mayor of the capital of Morelia state, denied ties to drug trafficking and urged the other candidates to accept the results.
Michoacan has long been dominated by drug cartels specializing in marijuana, heroin and methamphetamines.
It is President Calderon's home state, and he chose Michoacan to launch a targeted military offensive against traffickers in December 2006.
However, violence has persisted.
A PAN mayor was assassinated a week before the election while campaigning for Luisa María Calderón, and numerous candidates abandoned local candidacies out of fear.
But for the PRI, as unpleasant as Michoacan's elections may seem, a victory will help boost the party.
The man who is supposed to represent the PRI in the presidential election, Enrique Peña Nieto, speaking from Washington, congratulated Vallejo, saying, "I think this victory should be very encouraging, looking ahead to next year."
ADB urges Asia to help rescue eurozone
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has called on India and China to prepare to help rescue the eurozone from its sovereign debt crisis to avoid a long-term recession that would impede growth in Asian economies.
Rajat Nag, managing director of the Manila-based Asian Development Bank, said the world's two fastest-growing economies had to "do everything possible" to accelerate the economic bloc's recovery either through the International Monetary Fund or directly through bilateral agreements.
He warned against BRIC [Brazil, Russia, India, China] countries watching Europe's difficulties in an "even-handed" manner and said financial assistance from Asia along with European leadership and resources would help avoid a long-term crisis in the global economy.
"We're all in this together."
"So anyone who can help Europe out of the crisis is helpful," he told the Financial Times in an interview on the sidelines of the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
"Asia can be protected to some extent, but it cannot be immune."
"So if China and India can help, let it be by all means."
Europe's monetary union has been severely undermined by a sovereign debt crisis in recent months.
In recent days, Italy's borrowing costs have skyrocketed dangerously and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
Europe's ongoing sovereign debt crisis has raised fears it could push the global economy into recession and prompted calls for major emerging economies to come together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that any support from Asia would be channelled through the IMF, but said bilateral assistance – such as buying the bonds of the EU's rescue fund, the European Financial Stability Facility – offered greater bargaining power for Europe's Asian partners.
Anand Sharma, India's commerce minister, said "India is going to do everything it can" to help the eurozone as its own economy was now suffering from falling exports and drying up foreign capital inflows.
"Nobody wants the eurozone to remain unstable and turbulent," he said.
"We have monumental challenges and we have to maintain a high level of growth."
"It's not an option, it's an imperative, because where do we find employment for tens of millions of our young men and women?"
Others argue that developing economies like India have no responsibility to help wealthy Europeans when they face their own deep economic problems.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the US, said it would be politically very difficult to sell aid to Europe for India's one billion two hundred thousand people, of whom up to 800 million live on about $2 a day or less.
"At some point they will realize that Greeks retire at the age of 50 and go on vacation to the beaches and that will not go down well," he said.
Lee Howell, managing director of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India's reserves should be used to keep Greece's many well-paid public sector workers in jobs at poorly managed, loss-making companies like railways.
Mr Nag said the eurozone crisis threatens "major knock-on effects" across Asia.
The Asian Development Bank's forecast of 7.5 percent economic growth in Asia for 2011/12 now faces "downside risks" due to the threat from Europe.
He said vulnerable emerging markets needed to make "contingency plans" to protect themselves from a crisis and significant capital outflows from their economies.
Serious warnings from the Pentagon about possible defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta heated up Congress on Monday, warning that looming automatic budget cuts could undermine national security and set off a financial chain reaction from the halls of the Pentagon, to the battlefields of Afghanistan, to civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in reductions over the next decade, but now fears a further reduction of $600 billion or more in cuts that may be imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
"The impact of these cuts would be devastating to the department," Panetta said in a letter to Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Lindsey Graham, R-Calif.
He said Congress' failure to agree on the budget and its consequence, the so-called "sequester," would result in 23 percent global reductions and a halt to many new projects.
"Such a large cut, applied in this indiscriminate manner, would render most of our naval and construction projects unworkable — three-quarters of a ship or a building cannot be purchased — and seriously damage other modernization efforts," Panetta wrote to senators.
"We would also be forced to remove many of our civilian staff involuntarily and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we would almost certainly have to discharge civilians in order to meet the target."
"These changes would break faith with those who maintain our military and seriously damage goodwill."
The cuts would eventually catch up with combat troops, Panetta said.
"While wartime funding in the Overseas Contingency Operations accounts is not directly affected by the kidnapping, war efforts would be adversely affected by severe disruptions to base budgets," Panetta warned.
"Hiring of staff would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and supervision of the war-supporting contract."
"Payroll staff would be reduced, leading to delays in payments to suppliers in wartime, and legal and political support would be disrupted."
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days ago, asking for information about the possible impact of the automatic cuts on the Defense Department.
"The consequence of a hijacking of the Department of Defense would lead to a rapid decline of the United States as the world's leading military power."
"We stand firmly against this draconian action," the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they released Panetta's letter.
"This is not an outcome you can live with, and it's certainly not one we should impose on ourselves."
"Kidnapping is a threat to U.S. national security interests, and it must not be allowed to happen."
Whether Panetta's letter and recent warnings from senators will increase pressure for a budget compromise or intensify calls to exempt the Pentagon from cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly outspoken about potential cuts, even though he arrived at a job at the top of the Pentagon with years of budget experience in Congress and the White House and knowing he faced tough decisions.
At a press conference last week, the defense secretary painted a grim picture of what might lie ahead — an army with a shell, but not a core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a brigade without bullets."
"It's an air wing without enough trained pilots."
"It's a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough trained soldiers to accomplish the mission," Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a force that suffers from low morale, poor preparation and is not able to keep up with potential adversaries."
"Indeed, it invites aggression..."
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta sets out new details of how reductions "create significant operational risks: delayed response time to crises, conflicts, and disasters; severely limits our ability to be previously deployed and engaged around the world; and poses an unacceptable risk in future combat operations."
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could tackle the axe, including those already being tested and some only in the early stages of planning.
That list includes the F35 Joint Strike Fighter jet, a planned new bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new littoral combat ship and the new land-based combat vehicle that the Army and Navy need to replace, the humvee.
Halting development and further testing of the F35 could generate some $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but supporters say it's the vital next step in improving and tackling potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and pervasive deception and lying are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy trading sexual harassment allegations with several women; Each side accuses the other of lying.
Administrators at Pennsylvania State University have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "caught" with an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself with his denials quickly refuted by irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to covering up an extramarital affair.
And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been cases in which teachers have given the answers of the exams to the students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any given day, studies show that you can be lied to anywhere 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are white lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or "locating lies," is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charade, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades in prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars do look into each other's eyes.
They don't always stutter, babble, blush, or fidget.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can get to the truth by learning about statement structure, microfacial expressions, question formation, and timing.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-oriented lies," while women tell more "other-oriented" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less frequently to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they usually tell tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty for lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the subject's habitual behavior.
This is called "creating a baseline."
It helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristic.
You better know if someone normally taps your foot all the time so you don't make unfair accusations when you see your feet tapping in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for groups of deceptive behavior, verbal and nonverbal.
Consider these behavioral groups as red flags, not proof of deception.
Cheaters may freeze their upper body as they try to remember their story, point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a "post-interview vent" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the hard questions are over.
Interrogators often falsely make it appear that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the vocabulary of the subject.
Scott Peterson screwed up to the bottom and used the past tense while claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use distancing language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone may use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... as far as I know... to my knowledge."
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to uncover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances of avoiding being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
The controversial pipeline plan diverted after the threat of US delay in its approval
Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico -- infuriating unions while appeasing environmentalists -- the company seeking to build the pipeline says it is willing to redirect the project back on track.
TransCanada said late Monday it will move the planned pipeline out of Nebraska's ecologically sensitive Sandhills area, and is confident the project will win approval.
The company announced the decision at a news conference at the Nebraska Capitol.
TransCanada CEO Alex Pourbax says the company remains confident that eventually the pipeline will be approved, albeit with a different route.
This follows the State Department's announcement last week that they would delay the decision for a federal permit for the project until potential new routes are studied to bypass the Sandhills areas of Nebraska and the Ogallala aquifer, a vast underground water supply.
"This is a real path forward," Rep. Lee Terry, R-Nebraska, told Fox News.
The new environmental review ordered by the State Department may set aside any decision until 2013, after next year's election, though officials denied that politics was involved in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as the State Department's request, and expressed his full support for them.
The 1,700-kilometer pipeline would stretch from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would bring 700,000 barrels per day from the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
To do this, it would be necessary to cross six states.
It is hated by environmentalists, but loved by task forces, which have bet on the estimated 20,000 jobs linked to the pipeline.
But Nebraska lawmakers opposed to the plan are weighing legislation to force a move away from the Sandhills region and the Ogallala Aquifer, the largest source of drinking water and irrigation.
The State Department's current environmental impact study found that the project posed only limited adverse environmental impacts, but the energy industry source said the department's inspector general has ordered an independent test of the review process, focusing on two issues.
One is whether TransCanada's hired lobbyist, Paul Elliot, who was Hillary Clinton's campaign adviser in 2008, represents a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a firm that was hired to run the original studio was an inappropriate choice because it was tied to TransCanada.
Patti LaBelle Sued for Allegedly Causing Child to Vomit in Fear
A New York family claims disco diva Patti LaBelle behaved like a madwoman in the lobby of her Manhattan building, terrifying her young daughter to the point that she vomited in fear.
The "Lady Marmalade" singer's tirade scared 18-month-old Genevieve Monk so much so that she suffered "personality changes, sleep disturbances" and "increased her fear of strangers," her family says in Manhattan Supreme Court.
It was November 10 last year when stagehand Kevin Monk, his wife, Roseanna, a kindergarten teacher, and Genevieve were getting ready to go on a family trip.
While Kevin Monk was taking the car, Roseanna Monk went down to the lobby of the Riverside Boulevard building, with her luggage, carrying Genevieve.
Roseanna Monk said she stood near the door and put her daughter on the floor for a moment.
"Someone came up from behind and said, 'Do you know what your daughter is doing?' I said 'yes' and went to get her," he said.
LaBelle angrily admonished the pregnant woman.
"He said in an aggressive tone, 'You shouldn't have left your daughter near the door,'" Roseanna Monk said.
"I said, 'I have no interest in what you say or think.'
He became enraged and started using bad words - the word C and the word J out loud...
