Cut validates "analog blackout" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes that the world has undergone in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional controversies filed by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog blackout" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes necessary to invalidate it did not meet.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when issuing the decree that details the actions to be taken to complete the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft ruling, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a power reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero herself voted in favor of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree, and by admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions in it arranged for the digital transition.
The plenary session of ministers also decided to dismiss the lawsuit filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the minister president said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to prepare.
"Nor do I consider that doing so would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector correspond to the federal executive, who has by constitutional mandate, the rectory of the State.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has undergone in recent years, and translates into a better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing change, he argued, would be postponing the benefits of digitalization, which implies a decision of public interest, which does not have only a technical dimension, "since it covers economic, social, political and national security issues."
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic stewardship of the State, encompassing a group of attributions that the Constitution leads to the power of the State Executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and have done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the impugned decree, invades in any way the sphere of competence of Congress, since it is providing in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislature, he said.
Possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán analyzed
According to the data released by the PREP the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,074 total records.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where according to data provided by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent.  The votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,074 total records have not yet been counted.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just last November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local regulations with the federal reform in electoral matters.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Law of Electoral Justice, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal deadline so that they could enter into force in the present electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted their publication within the deadlines provided for in the Law of the Official State Newspaper.  on the grounds that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Branch and described as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state president to the constitutional reforms, since he does not have the right to "sanction or veto them."
Interviewed about the possibility of "voting by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial recount of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may occur in the event that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of scrutiny and computation in the file of the box or it is not in the possession of the president of the same; or, when there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the votes received in all the polling stations of the election may be carried out when there is an indication that the difference between the presumed winning candidate of the election in question and the candidate who has obtained the second place in the ballot is equal to or less than one percentage point; as long as at the beginning of the session there is the express request of the representative of the party and / or coalition that nominated the second of the candidates indicated.
The total count of the vote may also be carried out if, at the end of the ordinary count, it is established that the difference between the presumed winning candidate and the one placed second is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate came in second.  case in which the electoral packages that have been subject to partial recount will be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that in this situation is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total records.
