The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The designated prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed that country on the brink of economic disaster.
Italy's prime minister-designate Mario Monti will meet Italy's president on Wednesday to unveil the new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet on Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present to the president the outcome of his talks with political parties in his bid to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "framework is now well drawn," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, far less than normal, as Italy battles a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a harsh austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain battered confidence in Italy.
Underscoring pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability pushed the yield on Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to bail out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employers' association Confindustria, told reporters after meeting Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were boosted considerably by the backing of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support for the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because until now many of its members have opposed the technocrat-majority government Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in their efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
Italy's association of foreign banks added to the pressure by warning that a Monti failure would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organisations, on Monday.
It will end its round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite late last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would step down, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Rescuing Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone's current financial defenses.
Monti has said his government should last until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before bringing forward the elections.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist it should be made up only of technicians, an indication of their qualms about a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources said mutual mistrust and disagreements between the parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
