We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're fortunate to be friends with all of them still and we're honored to be a part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It's also very strange that a band like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, on its own, is much longer than many bands last.
Firstly, I think we are all fortunate to still be alive and, secondly, we all care about each other.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also opened that give each one freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other's music and it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy; However, thanks to their success, they have been able to do whatever they want.
How do they find a balance?
As we have grown, it has become easier to find a balance.
We make sure you're not too touring because it's easy to fall into that game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for the music, that reminds you to respect the music and what brought it, without being infatuated with being famous and being a rock star, something none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote really good songs and at first it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and never released a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were a lot of frustrations because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we are still very close friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a picture I think about the amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work,  laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was an amazing human being and we miss him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know his work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose it for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we are eager to see what Las Robertas can offer live and should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that comes to mind.
As a bass player, what are your influences?
There are so many.
Among the first ones that come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant despite no longer being a fad?
I think all of us always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the bands that came out at the same time, and, if there's relevance now, I think it's a wonderful thing because it's music worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
Why this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that maybe seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs although they may sound a little positive.
With both, when Ed touched them, I cried when I heard them and they are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there's some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs definitely represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
Peru:
Fujimori is hospitalized again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his 1990-2000 administration, suffers from several ailments, including tongue cancer for which he has undergone surgery four times and which is kept under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Canal N television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength of his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said that he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He was operated four times for cancer of the tongue, has a weight loss of 18 kilos to which other pathologies have been added such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreas cyst, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been imprisoned since September 2007 in the police's National Directorate of Special Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years' imprisonment for the deaths of 25 people at the hands of an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the early years of his rule.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and made up of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday in order to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderon, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political and commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayans residing in Mexico, according to the agenda released by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "conducive to the exchange of information on all political issues between the two nations," according to the Presidency of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country in a list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultation to its ambassador in the European country.
Since November, Mexico has chaired the G20, a group made up of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world, and has an agreement in force with the South American country since January of this year to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to expedite the realization of tax exchange agreements in order to get out of the "gray list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), formed by countries that did not implement all international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
In terms of trade, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004 that has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The mustachioed plumber goes through three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought, tirelessly, for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before had he done it in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the love of the girl in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which arrives this month in stores around the world, has been designed from the beginning to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS portable system, which allows you to play in three dimensions without the use of glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how stereoscopy should work without glasses," said the head of specialized press of Nintendo in Spain, Omar Álvarez, during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez indicated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game originally designed for that support", since until now successes such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesman has maintained that, despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
Alvarez has stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to hook less skilled users.
Once overcome, the most experts will be able to give a "second round" to the game levels, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This incursion of Super Mario in the three dimensions also means the return of the character to a portable console, a fact that has not occurred since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo winks at the followers of the saga and repeats the formula of success of the previous deliveries, consisting of the plumber with the mustache will have to travel platforms mined with dangers in order to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find novelties in the movements, environments, costumes and enemies and also a "playable" Luigi.
Colom endorses Portillo's extradition to the United States
President Álvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he processed the extradition of former president Alfonso Portillo to answer in the United States for the conspiracy to launder US $ 70 million.
Thus ends the process for Guatemala to respond to the request of the northern country that claimed Portillo to judge him there.
In a press conference, Colom said that his decision is due to the independence of the judiciary and executive, taking into account that a sentencing court had already ordered the extradition.
He asserted that during his mandate "he did not put his hands" in judicial resolutions and processed all the extraditions he has known.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquin, for murder and serious injury, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Victor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking, will be extradited.
What Colom did is an executive procedure after all judicial and constitutional instances were exhausted to prosecute the former president between 2000 and 2004.
According to resolutions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo must be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala has been resolved and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted for the embezzlement of Q120 million in the Ministry of Defense when he was president, which was the process that preceded the extradition, but the Public Ministry appealed and reactivated the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 at-risk youth
The entity was born to avoid the fall into the marginality of children without training
The balance of the first 25 years of life of the social support entity Trinijove is important: 6,000 young people at risk of exclusion have received help to overcome a difficult situation throughout this quarter of a century.
To this is added the hundred long jobs currently achieved for this social group.
The anniversary served yesterday to take stock of an event held in the old Fabra i Coats factory complex attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was born in the neighborhood of Trinitat Vella in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with little training, without work, with problems of dograddiction or in a situation of falling into marginality.
Yesterday's celebration in Sant Andreu concentrated a large number of heads of entities and institutions that in these 25 years have collaborated with the association.
The varied political representation, in the middle of electoral time, showed the unitary character of the work carried out by Trinijove.
Along with the president of the Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the event was attended by the former socialist Minister of Education, Ernest Maragall, and the former deputy mayor and current ecosocialist councilor Ricard Gomà.
The current Minister of Social Welfare and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the general director of the social work of La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa, also attended the great hall of Fabra i Coats.
Mas said that Trinijove was born in a very difficult time and that the current one is also difficult, but added that the work done so far "is a good basis."
The president gave Trinijove as an example for knowing how to fight against bad circumstances and for giving hope to people in difficulty.
"The crisis is not something new for the entity and for the work it does," he said.
Evicted a squatted farm where macro parties were held
The invaders had taken over 11 of the 13 floors of the building, in Balmes, 51
The 12 occupants left the farm at noon yesterday without offering resistance
Everything seems to indicate that the nightmare lived by the neighbors of 51 Balmes Street has come to an end.
Twelve people left yesterday noon voluntarily the building they occupied illegally, and where they organized macro parties that despaired the neighborhood, by court order and without the need for police intervention.
When the operation was over, the deadbolt on the door was changed to prevent a repeat of the situation.
"From now on there will be access control," said the administrator.
The squatters, who had invaded 11 of the 13 floors of the building -the rest are inhabited-, took all the electrical installation and part of the water, in addition to painting the walls and leaving residues of all kinds, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
The first three floors were the scene of the massive parties, which lasted up to two days and despaired the tenants.
Next to the building there is a nightclub, Balmes 51, which has also been damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat explained to Europa Press that since the building was occupied the business has dropped by 80%.
The owner of the nightclub points out that the invaders of the farm made unfair competition, since they sold the drinks at three euros, while in the disco they are worth 10.
In addition, the owner of the entertainment venue had had to respond to neighborhood complaints about noise, while, as she pointed out, the inconvenience is not caused by the customers of the disco, but by the inhabitants of the squatted house and, above all, the attendees of the parties that were organized there, which had increased their frequency and intensity in recent weeks.  according to angry neighbors in the area.
The head of the nightclub explained that the inconvenience was so great that she even reached an agreement with the owner of the property and nine months ago she "forgave" the rent.
The Guardia Urbana also confirmed that during the last weeks it had received more complaints from neighbors about the situation.
The president of the municipal group of the PP in the city council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had claimed last week "to immediately evict the property to end the problems of coexistence and civility that produce the neighbors, as well as the degradation of the area."
The popular leader explained that before the summer there was only one floor of the building occupied, but over the last few months the squatters had been entering all the floors of the building and almost all the floors, and that in some there have even been robberies.
In this sense, he added that, "it is necessary to end impunity and be forceful against the incivility that has been generated on the farm."
Also yesterday, the Mossos evicted a building in Nou Barris.
At 3.30 p.m. the police went to 35 rue de Mont-ral, after receiving a call from a neighbour who had observed that four people were entering the building.
All four were arrested at the time.
Park or mountain?
The architects agree on the timing of the call beyond controversies over fees
The municipal competition on the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-80s, at the height of the now extinct Metropolitan Corporation of Barcelona (CMB), this Administration printed some promotional posters of Collserola.
The brochure defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
Moreover, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with New York's Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park returned to the imagination of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital of the few that are not oriented in the north-south axis but above (mountain) -down (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a natural park results in this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with wild boars in the role of Yogi Bear.
In these were until, in September, the city council convened a mega-competition composed of 16 competitions for as many access doors to Collserola.
A door refers to the idea of park, without a doubt.
Either that or someone intends to put doors to the field.
The question comes alone: Collserola, park or mountain?
The competition, both for its purely organizational aspect and for what it means of reflection on the city, is the topic of conversation among all Barcelona architects.
It is almost a recurring theme to fall back on when two members of this ancient caste of chosen ones recognize each other in an elevator.
And this fact gives rise, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between what three Barcelona architects, and university professors, who have presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Mòdol and Marta Bayona: the contest is timely.
For Roldán, after addressing the coastal front "it is necessary" to discuss "the mountain front", since the speech of Ildefons Cerdà, that of the green apples, has not been carried out.
"It is worth starting from the basis that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things for its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex", says the architect for whom the title of "Collserola gates" contains a "lexical trap": we must not think of them "as the accesses to a park, but the delimitation of areas where you have to act".
Mòdol, like Roldán and Bayonne with experience in the urban world, describes the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Dangers derived from how "uncertain it is today to project public space" after the experience lived in the 80s and that had in the area of the Forum "its swan song".
The first fear is the very delimitation of borders on where it can be built.
"To limit something is to fix the next step", that is, its overpassing.
"We have to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [in reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM) ] can give rise to real disasters."
Closer to the question, Mòdol believes that, simplifying, the Vallès slope of Collserola "can be understood as a park, that of Barcelona, not", for a purely topographical matter.
Mòdol recalls that there is already a work done by the Patronat de Collserola that "should not fall on deaf ears", although he appreciates the opportunity that the city council offers his guild to intervene in this project "from the first moment".
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe-conduct that allows architects to enter the debate, but "doubts" whether it is this technical profile that should lead the multidisciplinary teams ("a success", he says) that have had to be created: "Architects should be just a tool".
Bayona insinuates that the answer to the question that gives title to this piece is complex, because in the bases of the contest there is a lack of a global vision of Collserola: "16 transversal competitions have been called," he says, "in the mountain-sea direction, but there is no longitudinal reading, which sees and understands the area as a whole."
This means, at least where appropriate, that it has chosen to participate in all 16 competitions.
Otherwise, a project for one of the doors may clash in program and definition with that of the architect next door.
In his opinion, yes, the city council should guarantee that the strip immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide, in all its extension, an area of facilities that makes a smooth transition between the city and the green.
Casino forgives Jonás Larrazábal and will go free
After 72 days of arraigo, the legal representative of the Casino Red granted the pardon to the brother of the mayor of Monterrey of the process that was followed for alleged blackmail
After spending 72 days in prison, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal will be released after the legal representative of the Casino Red granted him a pardon before the Second Criminal District Court, which continues a process for blackmail against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on the Casino Royale, the owner of the Casino Red, Sergio Gil García, made public a series of photographs and videos in which Manuel Jonás allegedly demanded the payment of an economic fee so that the Monterrey City Council would allow the clandestine operation of the bookmaker.
Following the public complaint, the State Attorney General's Office opened criminal proceedings against the brother of the PAN mayor and on September 2 he was detained and detained for 30 days.
After four hours before the Agent of the Public Ministry 3 in Patrimonial Crimes, he was transferred to the House of Arraigo 1, located in the Old Quarter of the state capital.
He remained there for the next 49 days when a second arraigo order was issued after the Public Prosecutor dismissed the crimes of bribery and organized crime.
On October 19, he was transferred to the Cadereyta prison for allegedly blackmailing the owners of the Casino Red with one and a half million pesos; However, he only spent a few hours in the medium-security prison as there were death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to continue the trial in the municipal cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, an arrest warrant was issued by the secretary of the Second Criminal District Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that after almost two months of investigations, sufficient evidence was verified to determine Jonás' guilt, such as the collection of 1.5 million pesos from the representatives of the bookmaker in exchange for allowing its operation.
This Monday, the legal representative of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, went before the judge José Luis Pecina to request forgiveness for the brother of the royal mayor; so in the next few hours he could regain his freedom.
During the legal proceedings, the agent of the Public Ministry assigned to the Court, Ramiro Arias, questioned García Gómez if the damage had been repaired and which of the partners of the bookmaker was the one who granted the pardon, although the lawyer tried to reserve the name.
Based on file 197/2011, the legal pardon is granted to Jonás Larrazábal and henceforth no claim can be filed regarding the process that was followed; In addition, no reparation of damage or punishment will be required.
After the hearing with the legal representative of the bookmaker, around 3:50 p.m. the immediate release of Larrazabal Breton was ordered.
The secretary of the Court, Jorge Yánez, went to the prison of the municipality of San Nicolás de los Garza to notify Jonás that he has been legally pardoned and his file will be archived.
He will also notify you of the immediate release order issued by the judge.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash where Interior Secretary Francisco Blake and seven others lost their lives
The Secretariat of Communications and Transportation (SCT) reported that the results of the accident where Interior Secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people lost their lives indicate that the helicopter was directly impacted on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were suitable for flying.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport personnel.
In addition, he said that in the investigations carried out in the impact zone, the appearance of pieces on the ground is not reported.
"In a search it is reported that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was structurally.
"The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to transport passengers.
The terrain has a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
For the moment, the secretary assured that it is a priority to have the results as soon as possible; However, the research can last several months, it could even reach a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, general director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was operating at cruising speed and that this happened on a soft ascending ground.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations the flight was carried out under the rules of visual flight, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM located adequate conditions for takeoff, as the aircraft advances towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico there were layers of cloudiness at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew has sought an area of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The impact coordinates and the last record of the radar aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a small area:
The information available so far allows us to assume that the impact occurred in a straight and sideways trajectory.
The pattern of dispersion of aircraft debris suggests that the helicopter was impacted on the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the crash, evidence remains undisclosed in the wreckage of any kind of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the field.
During the field work, pieces of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above mean sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably disarticulated along this route.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search over an area wider than the cordoned-off site around the crash, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found, reinforcing the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security conducts research to discover the gene for obesity in children and young people; is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover the gene for obesity in children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence', which will allow markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialty Hospital of the National Medical Center Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the research, the population, whether or not they are entitled to participate, is invited to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out on minors, every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of gathering 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
When World Diabetes Day was celebrated on November 14, he said that the objective is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on food.
They will also be asked about physical activity and inherited family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure taking, determination of glucose, triglyceride, cholesterol and insulin and genetic levels (it seeks to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for the markers is based on the fact that the country's population differs from others due to its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent of American Indian, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage and this condition is reflected in the genes that are associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows detecting if they have some degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the probability of suffering from metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors give it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting most of the day in front of the television and using means of transportation instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, that is, the greater consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetics that is analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of the UNAM, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the pavement were heeded, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 potholes each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who said that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement is adequate,  Potholes could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
In his lecture A technological opinion of potholes, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenos, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt is that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The CF researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pebbles that constitute the folder, he said, is bathed with asphalt.
When vehicles travel and generate efforts, it allows the forces to diffuse very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, they would spread even better, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt folder, he added, a last layer called rolling folder is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and diffuse the efforts, the rolling folder also requires having the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it greatly affects the performance of the asphalt binder.
When the ground gets wet, the water diffuses inside the folder and it is difficult for it to come out, this causes a softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a pothole, he said, the first to wear out is the bearing film and only then is the asphalt folder affected, but the damage does not occur instantaneously, but it is a process that should be attended to at the first signs with adequate maintenance programs.
The also member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicular load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always be in relation to the vehicular load and ensure that it is complied with, to avoid that potholes form frequently.
