Japan reborn after earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and puts an end to the spiral of falls that began in March
Since last March the Japanese economy was paralyzed, still convalescing from the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe suffered by the Japanese country since World War II.
The first estimates of the Tokyo government put the material losses at 300,000 million dollars, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have attenuated.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September served to turn the page, definitively: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% at an annualized rate.
The one recorded in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the fastest growth rate since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is explained, in part, by the rebound in the purchase of machinery to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decline in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first setback after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the real shock of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of crises to strengthen - or rebuild - infrastructure, to use shortcomings to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently represents 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable climbed 1%, driven by the increase in spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has entrusted itself to the domestic market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "safe haven securities" chosen by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the euro zone and the murky forecasts of the US, a privilege that weighs like a slab on the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic waterline is determined by the health of big tech groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, blamed their weak results between July and September on the yen.
While the markets continue with their siege on the peripheral countries of the EU, the government of Yoshihiko Noda does not lower its guard.
"We must be attentive to the risks that remain, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," Secretary of State for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa said yesterday.
