In fact, since 2002 this issue has been constantly monitored and a number of political offensives have been launched that have usually borne fruit.
The French do not get sick more than in the rest of Europe.
Let us first look closely at the national figures.
According to the French Social Security Institute (CNAM), more than €237 million in sick leave benefits were paid in 2006.
According to the French Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, subsidies for sick leave represented, in 2008, 5% of health expenditure, amounting to 11,300 million euros.
Of this sum, 46% corresponds to maternity and work-related leave, while 54% is related to sick leave, a figure that amounts to 6,200 million euros.
Consequently, 2.5% of health expenditure.
In 2010, the French took an average of 14.5 days off work, compared to 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
An average that undoubtedly hides deviations: another survey, published in 2007 by the Syrian professional management Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken a single day of sick leave.
Another study, in this case from Assurance maladie, indicates that in 2010 37% of sick leave lasted less than 8 days, 22% lasted between 8 and 14 days, 15% lasted between 15 days and one month, 15% between one and three months and 11% were longer.
Compared to our European neighbours, French workers are no more likely than in other areas to take sick leave.
A lengthy study carried out in 2010 by two CNRS researchers indicated that, between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate from work (for both health and other reasons) ranged from 10% to 11% in France, compared with 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom and between 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Fraud in sick leave is not particularly significant compared to undeclared work.
Fraud is quite limited in scope.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 has resulted in systematic checks on sick leave of more than 45 days.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million inspections, the CNAM found, in 13% of the 285,000 carried out, that short-term absences were "unjustified or too long", that is, 37,050 cases.
In the case of absences of more than 45 days, subject to systematic inspections, 11% of the cases were considered to be "duly adapted or unjustified; A figure that, taking as a starting point a total of 1.2 million, amounts to 132,000.
As a result, a total of 169,000 "unjustified" cases are reached among several million workers who took sick leave.
Undoubtedly, an insignificant figure in comparison, for example, with black work.
According to UMP MP Dominique Tian, author of a report on this issue in June, such a practice would represent tax revenue losses of between €9 billion and €15 billion per year, i.e. more than the total cost of sick leave subsidies and certainly considerably more than fraud in the latter area.
