Introduction of a budgetary "golden rule" in the Constitution
The government of the Social Democratic/Christian Democrat grand coalition that is in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to include in the Constitution a budgetary "golden rule" to reduce the public deficit and, thus, avoid a possible downgrade of Austria's sovereign rating by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor himself, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when Austrian public debt reaches 74.6%, a figure much higher than the maximum limit of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency were reduced by a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay 3 billion euros more in interest every year," said Christian Democrat Vice Chancellor for Foreign Affairs Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is thus responding to a request from the Brussels Summit to the member countries of the euro zone on 26th October last: in it the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, before the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the restoration of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in a law with equivalent value.
The device adopted by the Austrian Government is close to the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt this type of "rule".
Before 2017, the structural public deficit should decrease each year by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) and, from 2017, the structural public deficit of the federal state should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states, as well as communes, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is that, by 2020/2021, public debt will be reduced under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
