Energy policy:
Facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is one issue that cannot be dealt with taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is fitting that an election meeting should be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it considers the overall economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will mean the doubling of electricity demand before 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the increasing scarcity of fossil resources will have to be alleviated in order to continue producing electricity continuously, not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear power.
That is not the case either in Belgium, which subjects its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or in Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art power stations.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, Czech Republic, Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, are moving forward with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such a discourse.
The choice of Berlin will mean an increase in the price of electricity, greater energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, particularly from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions due to the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticeable.
Consideration should be given to the case of Denmark.
European champion in the wind sector, from which it obtains 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would detract from the realism of the wonderful declarations about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not express opposition on principle to this type of energy, polls show.
Let us remember that the energy policy of our country has lost to build an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Broadly export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specialising in international markets and which can create non-relocatable jobs.
If France were to decide to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of 6,000 million euros per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to operate sixty years, when its manufacturer is expected to collapse?
To solve the nuclear power equation, we must admit that there is no miracle source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva's development of low-CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a Safety Authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our highly professional teams are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, was produced under normal operating conditions; It did not cause consequences for people or the environment.
At Chernobyl, the accident was due to reactor design and unforgivable human failure.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented scope, which killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, just as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and cooperation between the security authorities and French and German operators and builders, the ERP presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is studied by all the electrical players who want to build a plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave them free to assume the leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticised from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with France's self-proclaimed status as a "country of human rights".
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the newspaper Libération of May 23) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters."
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the tone by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery in the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande limits himself to including banalities, indicating that co-development will solve the "problem of migration".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent paper summarizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among scholars on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth.  wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and hurts employment.
Fears about the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace domestic workers, particularly low-skilled workers, by pushing for lower wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and mainly work in sectors with no employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for personnel.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that has a lack of anaesthetists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to positively influence the salaries and employment of nationals.
Taking into account the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migratory flows means a rise in real wages in the long term of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies such as Google, Intel, PayPal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, contributing on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization calculates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to public budgets on average over his lifetime.
At the beginning of his mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the growth points that he lacked "with his teeth".
Such teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it only needs to think about a European democracy
Democracy is a precious commodity, but also a fragile one.
The European continent should be able to remember this because, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the twentieth century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some perhaps believed that, for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that it was something thought out.
Universal suffrage, although a necessary condition for democracy, is not sufficient in itself and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacolot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this respect, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return of the political sphere, but also the worrying feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be reflected upon in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer moving in a good way.
We will not gain if we demand a succession of national referendums, organised according to needs and in a disorderly manner.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a stop to the void of the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to strike blows, but a common, fully-fledged, calm and continuous exercise of options and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that bends to the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is Europe as a whole that suffers humiliation in the international arena.
We worry about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is the whole of Europe that slowly loses sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is for popular sovereignty to regain the helm of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare their future through investments.
A way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
Having fought for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
So be it.
But to think of it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being experienced as such by the citizens, would be a new folly and would lead us to a new stalemate.
We must enter a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" republicans.
Interest-driven Revolution would not be enough.
This lesson is still applicable.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
It can only be achieved by building a more politically democratic Europe, a genuine European popular sovereignty.
To build Europe, let us become Europeans.
