The world show of chip cards opens on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global sales of cards with microprocessors (bank cards, phones with SIM cards, etc.), with a total of 6,000 million units, according to calculations by the Eurosmart cabinet.
The most powerful segment is contactless technology, which allows you to pay for common transport or purchases simply by bringing the card to a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than last year!
Its share should continue to increase in 2012 (580 million units are expected) and represent about 10% of the global chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe, which has long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the contactless payment sector.
Around 26 million Visa bank cards already have this feature, which is accepted at 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards are being used.
But large stores work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCard cards this year.
To get the gear up, however, it is necessary for banks to make them available to their customers.
"There are two major French establishments that are committed to systematically disseminating contactless bank cards to their customers in the future," announces Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks test mobile phone payment
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Currently, there are few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, essential to carry out transactions.
"They're lagging behind."
"But it should finally experience a real boom next year."
"We anticipate that between 80 and 120 million units will be sold worldwide in 2012," explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But banks are taking the lead.
The bank Crédit agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhones of around 200 customers and collaborators will be equipped with a cover that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société générale also said yesterday that it is preparing to market an offer that allows its customers to pay contactless via their mobile.
From Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris worries about links between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
Links between the terrorist group Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqim) and the long-suspected Nigerian sect of Boko Haram have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Algiers already "has the certainty."
"The way both organizations operate and the intelligence reports show that they are cooperating," he said, without elaborating.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger last January reportedly resumed the catwalks.
Abducted from a restaurant in Niamey by people linked to Aqim, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The study of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers particularly caught the interest of researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who stayed for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria that is home to Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is allegedly close to Aqim and the sect.
"This is progress, but we certainly have to wait for more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqim and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is becoming more active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "supports" had become increasingly evident in the evolution and discourse of Boko Haram or in its modes of operation, which now involve the use of suicide bombers or explosive devices that are increasingly complex and similar to those used by Aqim.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pressuring Abuja to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long regarded the group as an enlightened community unworthy of interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (which means, in Hausa, "Western education is a sin"), encourages the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It is politicized and demands strict respect for sharia, while its militants throw themselves into the fight against the impious central government.
The latter are oriented in the first place to churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active and attacks on police stations multiplied.
The Abuja reaction was, as is often the case, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested in life, is killed in prison.
Since then, the sect is radicalized and abandons its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, he claimed responsibility for an attack that caused 80 deaths in Jos and, later, another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuja, in particular the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations becomes its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, stretching from Mauritania to Somalia to Nigeria, worries all security specialists.
While Aqim has attacked Mali and Niger and Al-Chebab's Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all information".
The World According to Republican Presidential Candidates
In relation to China, Iran, and aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete in simplicity and lack of knowledge.
Can an America weakened by crisis manage a complex world with simple or even simplistic ideas?
Listening to the Republican presidential candidates, voters might think so.
In recent days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the other candidates have been making more and more thunderous statements and shortcuts on foreign policy, traditionally a strong point of Republicans.
Slogans, often unfounded, are spread about China, Iran, aid to Israel.
Mitt Romney, the best-placed candidate in the race for the nomination by the "Grand Old Party", has threatened to take the Chinese to the WTO and denounce them "for manipulation of their currency", a key issue in an America exasperated by the migration of entire fragments of its sector to Asia.
It doesn't matter if that means the outbreak of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama's former ambassador to China and the only candidate with a sophisticated view of foreign policy, almost drowns in an attitude that "overwhelms" emotions.
He has called for a firm, but constructive, dialogue with Beijing (Obama's current position).
But Huntsman, who is stuck in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
Reagan style
Romney has also promised military intervention in Iran if sanctions fail to disrupt its nuclear program.
"If I get elected, I will stop Iran," he blustered.
"If Obama is re-elected, they will have the bomb."
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of having failed with his obligations to Israel.
Businessman Herman Cain, the second-highest ranked candidate, shows shameful ignorance of such issues.
Recently, he urged countering the Chinese military threat because Beijing "tries to develop nuclear capability", apparently ignoring the fact that China already has the military atom since 1964.
Texas Gov. Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants to intervene in Iran, says he is willing to deploy the U.S. military to Mexico to fight drug cartels.
The use of torture against alleged terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
The differences are considerable with 2008 Republican nominee John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
Opponents of the current president counter that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to loosen the piston in the fight against terrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of their naïve dialogue with Iran, on the hasty departure of the "boys" from Iraq and on their misrepresentations in Libya, and label it weak.
But the attacks are not easy for them.
The population judges in a rather positive way the national security balance of Obama, which killed Bin Laden.
From Iraq, he is wary of military interventions that generate a sinking.
And, arguing that it is necessary to rebuild America economically to resurrect his leadership, Obama gives the impression of being fairer.
Nord Stream, new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly links Western Europe with Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that communicates, directly under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
With this new pipeline, each year an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will reach Western Europe through a first 1,224 km crossing the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipe should be completed by the end of 2012 that will supply a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas, that is, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous work presents an air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the passage of land through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the Europe of energy, given that the project has generated a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in just five years, to make triumph its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, large consumers of gas and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," François Fillon confirmed during the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large contracts in the gas sector are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of Gazprom executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against ships' anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to take extreme measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs about 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted along its entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Swedish waters, but those responsible for the project gave it up when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state company to settle permanently in the sea off their coasts.
"In the event of a breakdown, we will interrupt the passage of gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But builders consider a leak unlikely, as they have predicted joints that are expected to leak every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline is monitored by an underwater robot, pulled by a vessel, which carries out external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides precise data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
At the beginning it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by Germany's E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Netherlands' Gasunie and France's GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased all the gas transmission capacity to Gazprom for a renewable period of twenty-five years.
"Gazprom will be paid for the total capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline has been carried out by 30% with the contribution of shareholders and 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7,400 million euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom alone bears the risk of expenses.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy shoreline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back a taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its off-white leaves, as if aged by time.
However, Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a design notebook, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was in charge of launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the stools.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to today's taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the twentieth century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become head of the brand at Modo Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Gone is the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had twelve employees in its beginnings, now has about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and has managed to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has managed to diversify its products: bags, diaries, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of disabled people are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is double the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Daunting?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organises the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable.
"Back then, the unemployment rate was not twice as high as the average.
"However, there is still a lot to do."
It is worth mentioning that the disabled unemployed continue to face numerous obstacles in accessing employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not completed high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
That is, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that "are the crux of the problem," says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; People's mindsets are advancing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"Now we reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body in charge of collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labor, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees in their workforce, compared to 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
Hazard: "A joy"
About to face the Bleus on Tuesday night (20h45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens do not hide the pleasure that this friendly match generates for them.
We will not dare to say that there was collusion between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting next to each other, on the stage of the Stade de France auditorium, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have really made peace.
Five months after his striker's gesture of resentment against Turkey, the Belgium coach has nothing but praise for him.
"I was very happy for Eden, for his progress and for him to be Belgian."
"I want to move forward," the Lille striker replies.
As for the contrast between his presentations in his team and in the selection, "it is a set", he has justified.
"I'm in Lille all year round, which doesn't apply to Belgium.
"I have to situate myself."
Called up to play Romania on Friday night, considering this match against France, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis to, finally, "shine".
Without forgetting the "pleasure".
He has been cheering for the Bleus since he was seven years old, as well as during the victorious campaigns of 1998 and 2000.
"I've always been his fan," he says.
Undoubtedly, this will especially reinforce the "particular" character of the meeting.
Especially since he will face "Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami)," he recalls.
"We just faced each other recently.
"Playing against them is always a joy."
Quite simply, Leekens has made reference to "pride".
"Pride" for playing "a gala match".
"Pride" also to verify, as a "neighbor", that France "is again a very high level team", about a year after Knysna's injury.
"Laurent Blanc has done a tremendous job," he said enthusiastically.
While Belgium will not attend the next European competition, the coach would be delighted to be able to share a plane with the Bleus to... Brazil, in 2014.
"Our little Belgians are growing up," he said.
"We're building something; The players are ambitious, they are hungry.
"You'll be able to see it in the next few games." Including the match against France.
Portugal shows a lot of confidence
Paulo Bento's Portugal faces with great optimism the second leg against Bosnia (22h00), which will be held on Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the first leg, both teams lacked realism.
"When these 90 minutes are up, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country."
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
He has no doubt; the Selecçao, which he has managed since September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012.
Indeed, only 90 minutes separate Portugal from happiness.
But there is a game to play and a rival, Bosnia, to defeat.
Taking into account the first leg (0-0), on Friday in Zenica's hell, it seems clear that the thing is not decided.
Portugal dominated the match for more than an hour, yes, but could not score the valuable goal that would have given them peace of mind.
"It's a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we didn't score away from home."
But at home, in the bright Stadium of Light in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced that they will pass, before a public that should be just as enthusiastic, even if it is evident that the match "is very even", dixit an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We hope the match will be very even, but we are completely convinced that we can take the lead," said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
"We still have a 50% chance of participating in Euro 2012," Carlos Queiroz's successor has relativized.
Friday's draw in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
The Bosnians could get a draw, although they also need to score.
"It's a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we haven't scored away from home," laments Bento.
"We are going to play against a team that has great technical quality and has players with great individual quality," he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will go with the intention of exerting, from the beginning, maximum pressure on the Bosnians to "not leave them time to think".
A good idea, provided that, this time, it is realistic.
